column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 NOON ON JUNE 11, 1997, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT GONDOLA CAR MW 190501, LOADED WITH CREOSOTE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND CLASSIFIED AS A SOLID HAZARDOUS WASTE, WAS LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID WHILE LOCATED IN THE RAILROAD'S STORAGE YARD IN PORTSMOUTH, VIRGINIA.  DUE TO THE PLACARD ON THE CAR AND THE COMMODITY DESCRIPTION ON THE WAYBILL AND HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST THIS BECAME A SUSPECTED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RELEASE INCIDENT AND A REPORT TO CHEMTREC AND ALL OTHER APPLICABLE AGENCIES WAS MADE.  IN ADDITION TO CHEMTREC AND ALL OTHER APPLICABLE AGENCIES, THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  AFTER INVESTIGATION, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS THE RESULT OF CONDENSATION CAUSED BY THE CONTAMINATED SOIL BEING WRAPPED IN A PLASTIC LINER. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ADVISED THAT THEY DID NOT CONSIDER THIS INCIDENT TO BE HAZARDOUS THREAT AND NO CLEAN UP WAS NECESSARY.  THIS REPORT IS BEING FILED TO KEEP THE RAILROAD IN COMPLIANCE WITH ANY REGULATIONS AND REPORTING REQUIREMENTS THAT MIGHT BE NECESSARY ONCE CHEMTREC AND OTHER AGENCIES ARE NOTIFIED OF AN INCIDENT.

column168: DOCK EMPLOYEE UNLOADED SHIPMENT THAT WAS BEHIND DRUM.  IT HAD A CORNER ON A SCRAPER BLADE PUSHED INTO DRUM. SUPERVISOR MADE A QUICK INSPECTION TO DETERMINE WHAT THE PRODUCT WAS, THEN PULLED DOOR DOWN, TELLING DOCKMAN TO REMAIN AWAY FROM TRAILER. HE THEN CALLED THE AAA COOPER SAFETY SPECIALIST AND SHIPPER RISK MANAGEMENT OFFICER WHO ADVISED USING A CLAY BASED OIL SOAK TO ABSORB ANY RESIDUE.  IT APPEARED THAT MOST HAD EVAPORATED BUT USED OIL DRI AND PULLED TRAILER AWAY TO AIR OUT.  HE ALSO HAD SHIPPER FAX MSDS SHEETS TO HIM.  AFTER TRAILER AIRED AND THERE WAS ONLY SLIGHT ODOR LEFT TRAILER WAS REPLACED TO DOCK AND UNLOADING COMPLETED.  CONSIGNEE WAS CALLED FOR DISPOSITION OF REMAINDER OF PRODUCT. column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: FROM ALL APPEARANCES SHIPMENT WAS INTACT WHEN ACCEPTED IN EWR. THE CONTAINER LEAKAGE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER PACKING. WHILE IN TRANSIT TO MIA THE DRUMS ENGAGED EACH OTHER CAUSING TOPS TO LOOSEN AND A LIQUID SPILL RESULTED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE AIRCRAFT/BIN 1. WHEN THE CARGO WAS UNLOADING THE SPILL WAS FOUND. (THE PASSENGERS HAD ALREADY DISEMBARKED BEFORE THE SPILL WAS FOUND.) THE DAMAGED HAZ CARGO CONTAINERS WERE IMMEDIATELY PLACED IN A HAZMAT PROTECTIVE CABINET AT GSE, TO PREVENT FURTHER CONTAMINATION W/ENVIRONMENT. A . IF THE METAL DRUMS HAD BEEN SECURED W/MORE INSULATING MATERIAL TO KEEP EACH DRUM SEPARATED (STYROFOAM OR NEWSPAPER) INSIDE THE WOODEN CRATE, IT IS QUITE POSSIBLE THAT THE HAZMAT WOULD NOT HAVE LEAKED AND THE ENTIRE INCIDENT WOULD HAVE BEEN DISCOVERED. B. ALSO THERE WERE NO ABSOLUTELY NO MARKINGS ON THE WOODEN CRATE TO INDICATE WHAT WAS INSIDE ESPECIALLY THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS, THEY WERE ONLY ON THE INNER DRUMS. ACTION TAKE INCLUDED DADE COUNTY FIRE DEPT HAZMAT TEAM, CHEMTEC AND DADE COUNTY DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WERE NOTIFIED AND THEY RESPONDED QUICKLY. DUE TO THE FACT THAT CONTINENTAL AIRLINES WAS NOT INFORMED THAT THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED HAZ-MATERIAL AND NO MSDS WAS PROVIDED BY THE SHIPPER, THE HAZ MATERIAL WAS NOT IDENTIFIED UNTIL SOME 20 HOURS LATER WHEN CONTINENTAL AIRLINES WAS ABLE TO RECEIVE A FAX OF THE MSDS FROM THE ACTUAL MANUFACTURER OF THE SPILL PRODUCT IN ITALY. SEE ATTACHED INFO: PHOTOS OF CONTAINERS, LABEL FOUND ON CONTAINERS, ACTUAL SHIPPERS INVOICE, COPY OF CARGO AIRWAYBILL AND CUSTOMS IN BOND DECLARATION.

column58: Basic Material; Basic Material; Weld or Seam
column168: AT 07:30 ON 06-10-97, A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGE (ACETONE UN1090) FELL OFF THE BACK BELT. AT THAT TIME, THE BELT WAS STOPPED AND THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER HANDLED IT CORRECTLY. THE PACKAGE WAS FORCED OFF THE BELT BY OTHER PACKAGES. APPARENTLY, WHEN THE PACKAGE HIT THE FLOOR, THAT IS WHEN THE DAMAGE OCCURRED, THE PACKAGE COULD HAVE HAD ADDITIONAL INTERNAL PACKING ALSO, THE SIDE RAILS OF THE BACK BELT NEED TO BE EXTENDED.

I SAW A PACKAGE ON THE BELT. I NOTIFIED MY SUPERVISOR, AND UTILIZING THE PPE I REMOVE PACKAGE TO RESTRICTED AREA. DUE TO EVAPORATION, THERE WAS NOT MUCH LIQUID LEFT IN BUSTED CONTAINER. WHAT HAS LEFT WAS ABSORBED WITH CLAY ABSORBENT. THE CLAY ABSORBANT SOLIDIFIED THE LIQUID AND WAS BAGGED AND DISPOSED OF. REMAINING HALF LITER WAS SENT TO CONSIGNEE.
RESPONDED TO CLERK AREA BOXLINE 4 DISCOVERED 5 OF 6 CANS DAMAGE. REPOURED DAMAGE AND RTS. DECONTAMINATED PPE.

OUR DRIVER AT A CUSTOMER SITE (FINDINGS INC.) TO MAKE A BULK DELIVERY OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. WHEN HE WAS UNREELING HIS HOSE LINE THE HOSE PULLED APART FROM ITS SWAGGED COUPLING. THE BREAK OCCURRED IN THE TRAILER'S CABINET WHERE THE HOSE IS CONNECTED TO THE HOSE REEL.THE HOSE IS APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET LONG AND 1 INCH IN DIAMETER. THE HOSE CONTAINED SOME AMMONIA LIQUID AND VAPOR, AND IT ESTIMATED THAT 10 TO 50 LBS. OF AMMONIA WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED ON SITE AND DISPERSED TO THE ATMOSPHERE. THE KEENE (NEW HAMPSHIRE) FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED, SIX (6) PERSONNEL FROM FITTINGS, INC. WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL AND RELEASED. THE EMPLOYEES OF FINDINGS (APPROXIMATELY 100 PERSONNEL) WERE EVACUATED FOR APPROXIMATELY 1 HOUR.

THE LOAD SHIFT CRUSHED ONE OF THE DRUM IN THE SHIPMENT ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM THE TOP CLOSURE ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH ABSORBANT PADS AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, THE DRIVER SECURED THE SHIPMENT USING A LOAD LOCKING DEVICE BUILT INTO THE SIDEWALL OF THE VAN TRAILER. THERE WERE NO VISUAL INDICATORS THAT THE LOAD LOCKING DEVICE WAS DAMAGED AT THE TIME THE LOAD WAS SECURED. THE DRIVER HAS BEEN ADVISED TO INSPECT THE CONDITION OF THE LOAD LOCKING DEVICE TO DETERMINE IF A CONDITION EXISTS THAT COULD CAUSE THE LOAD BAR TO FAIL DURING TRANSPORTATION. column168: UNLOADER WAS FILLING TOTES WITH DRUMMING NOZZLE.  TRUCK DRIVER WAS IN TRACTOR OPERATING PUMP.  AFTER 3 TOTES, UNLOADER TOOK OFF DRUMMING NOZZLE AND PUT HOSE INTO TOTE AND HOSE SLIPPED OUT AND DRIVER SHUT OFF PUMP.  UNLOADER CLEANED UP AREA WITH OIL DRY AND UNLOADED BALANCE OF TOTES.

DURING TRAILER INSPECTION ON 10-DAY TRANSFER YARD A LEAK WAS NOTICED COMING FROM A ROBBIE D WOOD TRAILER.  INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER LOAD REVEALED THAT A 55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM OF WASTE ACID HAD FALLEN OVER.  APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED ONTO THE PAVED PARKING LOT.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN UPRIGHT POSITION.  THE LEAK HAD OCCURRED FROM A SLIGHTLY LOOSE BUNG.  THE BUNG WAS RE-TIGHTENED. THE LEAKED MATERIAL WAS WASHED & OIL DRY USED TO ABSORB THE ACID AND WASH WATERS.  THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS ATTRIBUTED TO IMPROPER LOADING.  A SPACE WAS LEFT OPEN IN FRONT OF ACID DRUM AND DURING STOP AND GO TRAFFIC APPARENTLY FELL FORWARD.  THIS IN CONJUNCTION WITH THE LOOSE BUNG CAUSED THE SPILL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF SPILLAGE PRIOR TO PARKING AT THE 10 DAY FACILITY.

WHILE PERFORMING ROUTINE INSPECTION OF TRAIN M-BAALI-22, CAR INSPECTORS REPORTED A BLEACH-LIKE SMELL IN THE VICINITY OF TOW CHLORINE TANK CARS. THESE DEFICIENCIES WERE CORRECTED B 0310 MT.  ONLY VAPOR WAS RELEASED; THUS, NO REMEDIATION WAS REQUIRED.  THE SHIPPER HAS RECEIVED A COPY OF THIS REPORT.

WHILE LOADING THE FREIGHT IN THE AIRCRAFT, ONE CONTAINER WAS DROPPED.  THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER RUPTURED AND LEAKED LESS THAN 30 ML OF THE CORROSIVE MATERIAL.  CHEMTREC WAS CALLED IMMEDIATELY AND THE CLEANUP WAS ACCOMPLISHED PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF PROPERLY AND THE DAMAGED CONTAINER RETURNED IN A SALVAGE CONTAINER TO THE SHIPPER FOR RE-PACKAGING.  THE SPILL AREA IN THE AIRCRAFT WAS WASHED DOWN WITH WATER AND NO DAMAGE OCCURRED.

column168: WHILE WAITING TO UNLOAD, THE MARYLAND CHEMICAL DRIVER (WILLIAM TRUXON) OBSERVED A LIQUID LATER IDENTIFIED AS SULFURIC ACID DRIP FROM UNDERNEATH OF THIS TRAILER.  TRUXON IMMEDIATELY CHECKED HIS LOAD AND DISCOVERED ONE DEL DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUMS.  TRUXON STOPPED THE LEAK, PLACED THE DRUM IN A OVERPACK, AND NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL.  ALL CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED IN THE OVERPACK AS WELL AND TRANSPORTED TO MARYLAND CHEMICAL FOR FINAL DISPOSAL. RECOMMENDATIONS FOR IMPROVEMENT:  1. DRUM FILLERS AND HANDLERS WILL BE REFRESHED IN INSPECTING PALLETS FOR NAILS/OTHER PROTRUSIONS THAT COULD PUNCTURE DRUMS DURING STORAGE OR TRANSPORTATION.

ON 6/23, A BIRCH RUN DOCKMAN/DRIVER WAS OFFLOADING A PALLET OF STEEL COILS FROM A ROAD UNIT AT THE DOCK.  AS HE BACKED OUT OF THE TRAILER & SWUNG AROUND, HE RAMMED ON OF THE 16 DRUMS IN THIS SHIPMENT WITH THE PALLET HE HAD ON HIS FORKS.  THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY  LAID ON IT'S SIDE AND PIG PUTTIED SHUT.  CHEMREC WAS ADVISED.  THE SHIPPER GAVE US RETURN AUTHORITY ON THE BALANCE LEFT IN THE DRUM.  THE SUPERVISOR OF THE MOMENT REPROVED THE DRIVER AND A REPRIMAND IS TO BE ISSUED.

TRAILER #5009 WAS LOADED AT EASTMAN CHEMICAL ON FRIDAY 6/6/97 AND TRANSPORTED TO THE KINGSPORT TERMINAL OF SUPERIOR CARRIERS' TO AWAIT TRANSPORT TO LILLY INDUSTRIES IN HIGH POINT, NC.  WHEN THE ROAD DRIVER PICKED THE TRAILER UP ON 6/7/97, IT BEGAN TO LEAK WHEN HE MOVED IT ACROSS THE YARD.  SEVERAL DROPS FELL FROM THE DRAIN HOLES AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK NEAR THE LANDING GEAR, AMOUNTING TO A SPILL OF LESS THAN 1/2 PINT.  THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSLOADED TO ANOTHER TRAILER AND DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE. UPON INVESTIGATION, A 1' CRACK WAS FOUND IN THE HEAD SEAM WELD AT THE 7 O'CLOCK POSITION IN THE #3 COMPARTMENT.  THE TANK WAS REPAIRED AND RETURNED TO SERVICE.

TRAILER WAS LOADED AT EASTMAN ON 6/21/97 AND THEN PARKED AT THE KINGSPORT TERMINAL TO AWAIT TRANSPORT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION OF THE YARD, THE MECHANIC NOTICED A SMALL DRIP FROM THE #3 COMPARTMENT.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, HE FOUND A PINHOLE IN THE WELD OF THE #3 COMPARTMENT.  THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANK WITHOUT INCIDENT.  THE TRAILER WAS REPAIRED AND RETURNED TO SERVICE.

column168: VAPOR RECOVERY FAILED RESULTING IN SPILLAGE.

A DRIVER LEFT VALVES OPEN TO VENT OFF AIR PRESSURE WHICH HAD BEEN USED TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER LEFT THE AREA AND DUE TO THE SPILL AND MOIST WEATHER CONDITIONS A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD APPEARED.  A LOCAL POLICE OFFICER CALLED IN THE HAZ MAT TEAM BECAUSE HE DIDN'T KNOW IF THE TRAILER WAS LOADED OR UNLOADED. OUR DRIVERS ARE INSTRUCTED TO VENT TRAILERS BEFORE LEAVING THE CUSTOMERS FACILITY.  IN ADDITION, IN NO INSTANCE IS A DRIVER ALLOWED TO LEAVE A TANK UNATTENDED WHILE VENTING.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO ENSURE THEIR WAS NO RESIDUAL PRODUCT LEFT ON THE GROUND WHERE THE TRAILER WAS PARKED.

THE TRAIN CREW NOTICED THAT WHEN THEY MOVED THE TANK CAR A VAPOR (F0G) APPEARED AT THE TOP OF TANK.  WHEN THEY STOPPED MOVEMENT, THE VAPOR STOPPED. THEY NOTIFIED THE TRAIN DISPATCHER WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED ALL CONCERNED FOR A HAZMAT INCIDENT.

column168: UNLOADING WITH AIR PRESSURE (LESS THAN 25 PSI). 15 MINUTES INTO UNLOAD, CARGO HOSE RUPTURED @ SPOT JUST BEHIND CAM LOK FITTING CONNECTING HOSE TO CARGO TANK. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN CARGO TANK VALVE, BUT ESTIMATED 50 GALLONS SPILLED.  DRIVER CONTACTED SHIFT FOREMAN, WHO ACTIVATED INTERNAL RESPONSE TEAM. MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED & CLEANED UP BY WAH CHANG PERSONNEL.  MATERIAL WAS ON ASPHALT & DID NOT GET INTO AIR, WATER, OR GROUND.  CARGO HOSE USED FOR UNLOAD HAD BEEN HYDROSTATICALLY TESTED ON 10-31-96 (TESTED @ 150 PSI FOR 10 MINUTES). INVESTIGATION OF FAILED HOSE REVEALED WHAT LOOKED LIKE HEAT DAMAGE JUST INSIDE HOSE @ END OF FITTING SLEEVE (ON BOTH ENDS OF HOSE).  PROBABLE CAUSE OF HEAT-STEAM WAND INSERTED INTO ENDS OF HOSE DURING  CLEANING PROCESS.  PUT A DIRECTIVE OUT TO ALL ARROW CLEANOUT FACILITIES (COPY TO OUTSIDE CLEANING FACILITIES) TO AVOID PLACING STEAM WANDS INSIDE CARGO HOSES WHEN CLEANING, AS IT WILL DESTROY INTEGRITY OF HOSE.

TANK CAR RTLX 2109 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING SODIUM HYDROSULFIDE, 8, NA2922 FROM ITS INTERNAL HEATER COIL OUTLET.  RESPONDER FROM THE CONSIGNEE WAS CONTACTED AND INVESTIGATED.  UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR'S HEATER COIL PIPES HAD FAILED AND PRODUCT FILLED THE PIPES.  THE HEATER COIL'S INLET AND OUTLET CAPS WERE APPLIED STOPPING THE RELEASE.  THE CAR WA UNLOADED AND SENT TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIR. NOTE: CAR BUILT DATE 1/1967.  INBOUND TRAIN: NM071 09.

TRAILER ARRIVED WILLOW SPRINGS HUB LEAKING THICK CLEAR LIQUID SUBSTANCE FROM THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  LIQUID ALSO LEAKED ON THE DECK OF THE FLATCAR RTTX 165443.  UPON INSPECTION BY BNSF HAZMAT RESPONDER, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT DRUM OF RESIN SOLUTION HAD DEVELOPED A LEAK AT THE BOTTOM JUST ABOVE THE ROLLING HOOP DUE TO RUBBING AGAINST OTHER DRUMS IN LOAD. THE CONTENTS OF THE 55 GALLON DRUM LEAKED INTO THE TRAILER AND CONTAMINATED OTHER ARTICLES IN THE SHIPMENT.  SHIPPER'S CONTRACTOR DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER, FLAT CAR AND DISPOSED OF CONTAMINATED ARTICLES.  THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE A DETERMINED TO BE LACK OF BLOCKING AND BRACING BY THE SHIPPER.

LOOSE NUTS ON "B" END LIQUID VALVE MOUNTING, ACFX 19919, JUNE 12, 1997, PHILADELPHIA DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0900 HOURS, THURSDAY, JUNE 12, 1997, A CONRAIL CAR INSPECTOR AT CONRAIL'S ALLENTOWN YARD IN PHILADELPHIA, PA REPORTED ODOR ORIGINATING FROM TANK CAR ACFX 19919 CONTAINING AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, LIQUEFIED. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1150 HOURS, CONRAIL'S  MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FIELD SERVICES ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THE CAR HAD TWO OF FOUR NUTS LOOSE ON "B" END LIQUID VALVE MOUNTING.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1440 HOURS, TWO REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE CONSIGNEE, LAROCHE ARRIVED AT THE SITE. REPAIRS WERE MADE BY CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FIELD SERVICES MANAGER AND LAROCHE REPRESENTATIVES WHO SECURED THE LEAK BY CROSS-TORQUING THE MOUNTING FLANGE SECUREMENT NUTS.  TWO OF THE FOUR NUTS WHERE THE LEAK WAS ORIGINATING FROM (RIGHT SIDE OF VALVE, VALVE OPERATING HANDLE SIDE) REQUIRED APPROXIMATELY 1 3/4 TURN EACH FOR SECUREMENT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 HOURS, CAR SECURED AND OKAYED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

A TANK CAR AT CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN PARKERSBURG, WV, WAS REPORTED TO HAVE VENTED SOME VAPORS FROM THE TOP WHEN COUPLED INTO DURING SWITCHING.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER (OF THE LAST LOAD) WAS NOTIFIED.  THE SHIPPER RESPONDED.  THEY FOUND THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE PHLANGE WAS LOOSE AND WHEN THE CAR WAS COUPLED INTO, IT CAUSED THE GASKET TO LEAK SOME VAPORS.  THE PHLANGE SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

A SWITCH CREW WAS MOVING SOME CARS IN A TRACK AT THE BIDS (BULK INTERMODAL DISTRIBUTION SERVICES) TERMINAL IN PHILADELPHIA, PA, WHEN THEY SAW A VAPOR CLOUD FORM OVER UTLX 12149.  THE CARS WERE SHOVED BACK IN THE TRACK AND LEFT ALONE.  THE TRAINMASTER  INSPECTED THE CAR AND DID NOT SEE ANY SIGN OF PRODUCT RELEASE.  BIDS PERSONNEL REMOVED AND BROKE DOWN ALL LOADING/UNLOADING FITTINGS TO IDENTIFY A SOURCE OF THE VAPOR RELEASE.  THEY FOUND THAT THE AIR FITTING HAD DAMAGE TEFLON TAPE ON THE THREADS AND POSSIBLY THE SOURCE OF THE VAPOR RELEASE.  NEW TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED AND THE FITTING WAS PUT BACK IN PLACE.

column168: WHILE MAKING OUTBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION, A CAR INSPECTOR DISCOVERED THAT GATX 29880 WAS DRIPPING LIQUID FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  THE CAR IN QUESTION WAS SEPARATED FROM THE TRAIN AND MOVED A SHORT DISTANCE TO AN ISOLATION TRACK. AN EMERGENCY REPAIR CREW WAS CALLED TO CONTAIN THE LEAK.  CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS LOOSE.  THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED WITH A 36' PIPE WRENCH AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE AREA WHERE THE MATERIAL HAD SPILLED WAS CLEANED AND THE MATERIALS DISPOSED OF.  THE TANK CAR WAS REINSPECTED AND FINDING NO EXCEPTIONS THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: EMPLOYEES WORKING AROUND TANK CAR UTLX 84592 OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE AREA AROUND THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ON A SIDE TRACK.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION AND RESPONDED TO THE YARD TO INSPECT THE TANK.  THE SHIPPER'S PERSONNEL FOUND THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN OVERLOADED AND LIQUID PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED THROUGH THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE SHIPPER TRANSLOADED APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM THE TANK TANK INTO TRUCKS.  THE TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED AND FINDING NO EXCEPTIONS THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: A MARKED COVERED GONDOLA WAS REPORTED TO BE SPILLING LIQUID BY A SWITCH CREW. ASSESSMENT BY BNSF RESPONDERS LOCATED NUMEROUS AREAS OF SPILLED PRODUCT IN SEVERAL TRACKS AT THE EAST END OF THE YARD OPERATIONS WERE SUSPENDED UNTIL INITIAL REMEDIATION WAS COMPLETED. THE CULPRIT CAR WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO HAVE A DAMAGED TOP CHORD ON THE "A" END OF THE CAR THAT PREVENTED A CLOSURE OF THE COVER. THE COVERS HAD ALSO SHIFTED ABOUT "6" AWAY FROM THIS END OF THE CAR. WHEN CHECKED THROUGH THE HATCHES ON THE COVER, ALL PRODUCT APPEARED TO BE OF THICK LIQUID VISCOSITY. THE SHIPPER'S CONTRACTOR REMEDIATED PRODUCT ON THE GROUND AND ON THE CAR. LIQUID WAS PUMPED FROM THE SLUDGE-LIKE MATERIAL REMAINING IN THE CAR. CAR WILL NOT CONTINUE IN RAIL TRANSPORTATION AS A LOAD. ARRANGEMENTS HAVE BEEN MADE TO REMOVE PRODUCT FROM THE CAR.

DURING THE CHANGEOVER THE ROAD DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID LEAKING OUT THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  HE THEN BACKED THE TRAILER UP TO THE DOCK AND INSPECTED FREIGHT. ON JUNE 19 1997 ON OR ABOUT 0900 HRS IT WAS REPORTED TO GULF CARIBE MARITIME REPRESENTATIVE, JOHN BATES THAT A RAIL TANK CAR LOADED WITH HCL 22% WAS LEAKING ON THE OCEAN DECK BARGE CHEMCARIBE.  THE BARGE CHEMCARIBE IS IN TRADE HAULING RAILCARS FROM MOBILE, AL TO PONCE PR WITH VARIOUS DIFFERENT CHEMICALS.  AFTER THE REPORT OF THE LEAK I (JOHN BATES) ARRIVED AT SITE AT 0910 HRS AT THSI TIME ALABAMA STATE DOCKS ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT TEAM AND SECURITY WERE ALREADY ON SITE, THE LEAK WAS EVALUATED AND AT 0915 HRS THE US COAST GUARD WAS CALLED ALONG WITH MOBILE FIRE AND RESCUE AND HAZMAT TEAM.  AT 0928 HRS FERGUSON HARBOUR HAZMAT REAM WAS CALLED AT 0935 HRS ADEM WAS ADVISED OF THE SITUATION, 1000 HRS. MR WILL CATLTON WITH FERGUSON HARBOR ARRIVBED AT SITE AND ADVISED ME IT WOULD BE 4 HOURS UNTIL HIS TEAM COULD BE ON SITE.  APPROX ONE HOUR LATER THE MOBILE FIRE AND HAZMAT REAMS DEPARTED ALONG WITH THE US COAST GUARD OPNCE THERE WAS NO THREAT TO PERSON ON PROPERTY.  THE MOBILE POLICE HAZMAT TEAM KEPT TWO PERSONNEL ON SITE ALONG WITH ME TO KEEP A CHECK ON THE LEAK UNTIL FERGUSON HARBOR PERSONNEL COULD ARRIVE.  AT 1000 HRS VULCAN CHEMICALS WAS ALSO ADVISED OF THE SITUATION WITH THERE RAILCAR, THEY ALSO HAD CONVERSATION WITH FERGUSON HARBOR ABOUT STOPPING THE LEAK AND CLEANING UP THE SPILL.  ON OR ABOUT 1500 HRS FERGUSON HARBOR PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SITE AND AT 1600 HRS THE LEAK WAS STOPPED, THE RAILC AR WAS FOUND TO HAVE A LOOSE DISCHARGE FLANGE.  THE FLANGE WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND SATISFACTORY AT THIS TIME ALL BOTS TO FLANGE CONNECTIONS WRE TIGHTENED.  THE US COAST GUARD WAS NOTIFIED THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND ALL WAS SECURE AT THIS TIME ALL AGENCIES DEPARTED THE SITE.  ON JUNE 20 1977 1100 HRS FERGUSON HARBOR RETURNED TO THE BARGE TO DECONTAMINATE THE RAILCAR AND THE DECK OF THE BARGE AT 1300 HRS DECON WAS FINISHED AND TEH LASHING CREW RETURNED TO THE BARGE TO PREPARE THE BARGE FOR SEA.

VAN TRUCK) TO OVERTURN. VEHICLE #1 PROCEEDING FURTHER LOST CONTROL, OVERTURNED AND SKIDDED OFF THE ROADWAY ONTO THE RIGHT GRASSY SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. OUR DRIVER INADVERTENTLY OVER FILLED THE DIESEL TANK WHILE UNLOADING.  AS THE TANK FILLED UP, IT FORCED THE CAP OFF OF THE REMOTE FILL CONNECTOR.  THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING STRAIGHT INTO THE TANK. THESE SORBENTS WERE PLACED IN A DRUM AT OUR FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL.  JOHN SCOTT FROM ALERT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (219-921-0006) ALSO HELPED THE DRIVER WITH THE CLEAN UP.  KANEY TRANSPORTATION PERSONNEL PUT CHEM-OIL-AWAY ON AFFECTED AREA, THEN SWEPT IT BACK UP FOR FUTURE USE.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING HIS TRUCK AT THE GAS STATION AND HAD JUST UNLOADED THE FRONT COMPARTMENT OF THE TRUCK.  HE MOVED THE PRODUCT HOSE TO THE BACK COMPARTMENT OF THE TRUCK, LOCKED IT IN PLACE, AND SLOWLY OPENED THE DISCHARGE VALVE. HE TURNED AWAY FOR ABOUT 30 SECONDS AND WHEN HE LOOKED BACK, HE SAW A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND UNDER THE DISCHARGE VALVE.  UPON OBSERVING THE SPILL (1QUART) HE SHUT OFF FLOW AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL USING SPILL PADS.  WE WILL DISCUSS THIS INCIDENT AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING.  DRIVERS WILL BE ENCOURAGED TO PLACE SPILL PADS UNDER UNLOADING MANIFOLD TO "CATCH" ANY SMALL DRIPS.  ALL SPILL MATERIALS WERE RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ON JUNE 29, 1997 AT 0520 HRS. A SEMI-TRUCK/CARGO TANK COMBINATION FROM OUR FLEET OVERTURNED ON THE NORTH BOUND ENTRANCE RAMP TO I-85 AT COX RD IN GASTONIA, NC.  THE DRIVER APPARENTLY WAS EXCEEDING A SPEED SAFE ENOUGH TO MAKE THE TURN.  THE CARGO TANK WAS LOADED WITH 8500 GALLONS OF GASOLINE.  APPROXIMATELY 1000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS SPILLED THROUGH A PUNCTURE IN THE CARGO TANK.  THE GASOLINE WAS ABSORBED INTO THE SOIL AND SOME RUNOFF WENT INTO STORM DRAINS WHICH DISCHARGED INTO DUHART CREEK. WITHIN ONE AND ONE HALF HOURS OF THE ACCIDENT ACTION ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY HAD EQUIPMENT AND PERSONNEL ON THE SCENE AND INITIATED CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES.  THEY IMMEDIATELY SET UP BOOMS DOWN STREAM AND DIVERTING THE RUNOFF TO A PAVED COLLECTION AREA.  THE GASOLINE THAT WAS DIVERTED TO THE COLLECTION AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY PUMPED INTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK.  THE GASOLINE THAT SPILLED INTO THE CREEK WAS ABSORBED BY THE BOOMS AND OTHER ABSORBENT MATERIALS PLACED ALONG THE STREAM. THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF THROUGH A WASTE HANDLING CONTRACTOR.  STAT, INC., CONTRACTED BY ACTION ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY, EXCAVATED AND TRANSPORTED APPROXIMATELY 1436 TONS OF AFFECTED SOIL.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS TRANSPORTED TO SOIL TECHNOLOGIES, 947 CROWDER RD, SHELBY, NC, A LAND FARMING FACILITY.  THE SOIL EXCAVATION BEGAN AT APPROXIMATELY 1300 HOURS ON THE DAY FOR THE ACCIDENT SEVEN HOURS AFTER THE ACCIDENT AND CONTINUED FOR FIVE DAYS.  WE UNITED OIL OF THE CAROLINAS, INC. HAD EQUIPMENT AND PERSONNEL ON SCENE TO BEGIN OFF-LOADING OF THE GASOLINE CARGO WITHIN TWO HOURS OF THE ACCIDENT.  THE HAZ-MAT TEAM OF THE CITY OF GASTONIA FIRE DEPARTMENT WOULD NOT ALLOW THE OFF-LOADING PROCESS TO BEGIN UNTIL 1100 HOURS SOME FOUR AND ONE HALF HOURS AFTER THE A ACCIDENT. SINCE THE CARGO OF GASOLINE WAS LEAKING DURING THIS ENTIRE TIME WE FEEL THE SEVERITY OF THE CONTAMINATION WAS WORSENED. THE ACCIDENT SCENE AND SURROUNDING AREAS WERE NO MORE STABLE AT 1100 HOURS THAN TWO HOURS PREVIOUSLY, BECAUSE OF THE CONTINUING LEAK.  WE UNDERSTAND THAT SAFETY TO HUMAN LIFE WAS OF FIRST CONCERN AND APPRECIATED THAT CONCERN BUT HOPEFULLY SOME THINGS WERE LEARNED FROM THIS EXPERIENCE.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1730 HOURS MONDAY JUNE 30, 1997, AT CONRAIL'S BEACON PARK YARD IN BOSTON, MASSACHUSETTS, A CONRAIL CAR INSPECTOR REPORTED SMOKE EMITTING FROM THE FRONT OF TRAILER UPSZ 846879 CONTAINING FLAMMABLE SOLIDS, ORGANIC, N.O.S. (TOY PROPELLANT DEVICES). APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1740 HOURS, JUNE 30, 1997, THE BOSTON FIR AND POLICE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED. AT APPROXIMATELY 1731 HOURS, REACT, A CONTRACT ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION COMPANY ARRIVED AT THE SITE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1945 HOURS, BOSTON DEP ARRIVED AT THE SITE. AT APPROXIMATELY 2015 HOURS, REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE SHIPPER UNITED PARCEL SERVICES ARRIVED AT THE SITE. AT APPROXIMATELY 0001 HOURS, JULY 1, 1997, THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED AND THE EVACUATION WAS CANCELED. THE TRAILER WAS DESTROYED AND THE ENTIRE LOAD WAS CONSUMED. AT APPROXIMATELY 1350 HOURS, JULY 1, 1997, THE SHIPPER UNITED PARCEL SERVICES TOWED THE TRAILER BODY OFF CONRAIL'S PROPERTY. WHILE INSPECTING CARGO, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT EIGHT (8) DRUMS HAD PINHOLES IN THE LIDS CAUSED BY THE CORROSIVE NATURE OF THE PRODUCT.  THE KIESEL COMPANY WAS CONTRACTED TO WORK THE LOAD AND PREPARE FOR TRANSPORTATION.  FURTHER INSPECTION BY KIESEL REVEALED THAT THE LIDS WERE NOT LINED TO PREVENT THE CORROSIVE ACTION OF THE PRODUCT AND AS A RESULT WERE BEING EATEN BY THE ACID.  ALL OF THE LIDS WERE REPLACED BY THE CONTRACTOR.  MATERIAL SPILLED ON TRAILER FLOOR WAS PICKED UP WITH ABSORBENTS AND PLACED IN AN OVERPACK CONTAINER.  LOAD PROCEEDED ON TO DESTINATION WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEMS ENCOUNTERED.

column168: TRI-STATE MOTOR TRANSIT WAS ADVISED AT 06:05 SATURDAY, JUNE 28, 1997, BY THE NEW MEXICO HIGHWAY PATROL THAT ONE OF OUR TRUCKS HAD A DRUM SPONTANEOUSLY COMBUST.  THIS OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 03:30 CDT.  BOTH EAST AND WEST BOUND TRAFFIC ON 1-40 WAS REROUTED AROUND THE TRUCK.  THIS OCCURRED AT MM 178 ON I-40 EASTBOUND.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO DISCONNECT THE TRACTOR FROM THE TRAILER.  NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, REPORT NO. 393160 AT 06:30AM.  THE DRUM THAT BURNED WAS A 30 GALLON POLY CONTAINING 7, 1 POUND PACKAGES OF SMOKELESS POWDER AND 2, 5 POUND PACKAGES OF SAME.  THIS WAS COLLECTED IN THE LOS ANGELES AREA FROM A HOUSEHOLD HAZARDOUS WASTE DRIVE.  AS OF THIS DATE, WE HAVE NOT BEEN ADVISED BY THE SHIPPER/CUSTOMER OF THE CAUSE FOR THE DRUM AND CONTENTS BURNING. THE OTHER CONTAINERS ON THE TRUCK WERE NOT BROACHED IN ANY MANNER BY THE FIRE.

A LIFE-SAVING APPLIANCE, SELF-INFLATION, WAS PACKAGED IN A WRAPPING MADE OF THE SAME MATERIAL AS THE RAFT.  AS THE PACKAGE (74"X13"10") WAS BEING HAND LOWERED ONTO A WOODEN PALLET THE TWO GAS CYLINDERS ATTACHED TO THE RAFT BECAME ACTIVATED, INFLATING IT.  THE PEOPLE IN THE VICINITY MOVED OUT OF THE WAY, AND THE FULLY INFLATED RAFT (APPROXIMATELY 17'X15'X13') WAS CARRIED TO A QUIET AREA.  IT WAS THERE DEFLATED.  SOME MEMBERS OF THE SHIPPING ORGANIZATION CAME TO INSPECT THE ITEM AND WERE TOLD THAT IT WOULD BE HELD IN A SECURE AREA UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE.  THE DEFLATED RAFT WILL BE PUT IN A "D" CONTAINER AND STORED.  THE SHIPPERS WERE NOTIFIED OF THE FACT THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS INCORRECTLY PACKAGED, WITHOUT DOCUMENTS, MARKING AND LABELLING.

column168: DRIVER STOPPED AT REST AREA AND NOTICED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM BACK OF TRAILER.  HE CALLED 911, AND THE PA STATE POLICE RESPONDED AND ALSO CALLED IN THE CUMBERLAND COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM (S.H.O.T.) - HAZMAT RESPONDERS FOUND REAR CLEANOUT CAP ON TOP OF TRAILER TO BE LOOSE AND LEAKING, AND 3  OTHER CAPS THEY JUDGED TO BE LOOSE. THEY TIGHTENED SAME TO STOP LEAK.  CARRIER SENT 1 HAZMAT TRAINED RESPONDER, WHO RECHECKED CAPS AND PLACED TEFLON TAPE AS SEALANT - REPORTED BACK TO INCIDENT COMMANDER, AND THE TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.

OUR DRIVER DISCOVERED THE SPILL WHILE MAKING A ROUTINE LOAD/TIRE CHECK.  OUR VAN TRAILER WAS EQUIPPED WITH SECONDARY CONTAINMENT.  THIS PREVENTED ANY MATERIALS FROM ESCAPING THE TRAILER.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE AND HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. BELLEFONTAINE, MO, WAS CONTACTED TO PROVIDE CLEAN UP.  THE HERITAGE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM DETERMINED THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL TO BE THE GENERATOR'S FAILURE TO INSTALL THE O-RING SEAL ON THE DRUM.  THE SPILLED LIQUID WAS ABSORBED AND THE AREA WAS DECONTAMINATED.  ALL CONTAMINATED SOLID MATERIALS WERE PLACED IN THE EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON OVERPACK THAT HAD LEAKED.  THE STEEL DRUM CONTAINING THE LIQUID WAS PLACED IN A NEW EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON POLY OVERPACK WITH THE PROPER SEAL TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE.

OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING A ROLLOFF BOX FROM THE ROLL OFF TRAILER. THE INCREASED STRAIN OF THE LOAD SHIFTING TO THE BACK OF THE BOX DURING UNLOADING CAUSED THE SEAL TO LEAK. OUR DRIVER AND PERSONNEL AT ENSCO STOPPED THE LEAK BY TIGHTENING THE CENTER LATCH ON THE TAILGATE OF THE BOX. DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO CHECK AND TIGHTEN ALL TAILGATE SECUREMENT DEVICES BEFORE LOADING OR UNLOADING BOXES. ADDITIONALLY DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO CHECK BOXES FOR FREE STANDING LIQUIDS BEFORE LOADING OR UNLOADING BOXES. IF LIQUIDS ARE PRESENT THEY MUST EITHER STABILIZE THE LIQUIDS OR HAVE THE LIQUIDS PUMPED OFF.

IN ADDITION, 2 DAMAGED CHLORINE CARS WERE TRANSLOADED. FIVE CONTRACTOR EMPLOYEES CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE SPILLED SODIUM HYDROXIDE AND RECEIVED FIRST AND SECOND DEGREE CHEMICAL BURNS. THREE WERE TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL, TREATED AN RELEASED.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRAIN Q30207 STRUCK THE REAR OF TRAIN V60105 RESULTING IN THE DEATH OF THE ENGINEER ON Q302 AND DERAILING 4 COAL HOPPERS IN V601, 2 LOCOMOTIVES AND 15 CARS Q302.  FIVE HAZMAT CARS WERE DERAILED; 1) A LOAD OF AMMONIA NITRATE, 2)  A LOAD OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE, 3)  A RESIDUE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, 4) A LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID,, 5)  A LOAD OF ACETALDEHYDE.  THE ACETALDEHYDE CAR (ETCX 29087)  WAS PUNCTURED WITH A COUPLER ON THE A END.  THE RELEASE PRODUCT CAUGHT FIRE & BURNED FOR SEVERAL HOURS.  ABOUT 200 PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED INITIALLY.  ALL BUT 5 FAMILIES WERE PERMITTED TO RETURN HOME ON 7/8. LOCAL STATE & FEDERAL AGENCIES RESPONDED.  THE SULFURIC ACID WAS TRANSLOADED FROM SAZX 21600 TO SAZX 21464. APPROXIMATELY 19000 GALLS OF ACETALDEHYDE WAS CONSUMED IN THE FIRE. THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE AND AMMONIUM NITRATE CARS WERE RERAILED WITHOUT DIFFICULTY.

column14: OFF OF EXIT #56 OFF OF I-75
column168: THE TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS SOUTHBOUND ON 1-75 NEAR NIOTA, TN HAVING MADE AN EARLIER DELIVERY. AFTER MAKING THAT DELIVERY, THE PRESSURE ON THE TRAILER WAS BLOWN DOWN TO 75 PSIG USING THE VENT STACK INSTALLED AT THE CUSTOMER UNIT. DURING A ROUTINE STOP TO CONDUCT A TIRE CHECK AND A CHECK OF THE CARGO TANK PRESSURE, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE PRESSURE IN THE CARGO TANK HAD RISEN TO 138 PSIG, IN EXCESS OF THE ANTICIPATED PRESSURE RISE FOR A HYDROGEN TRAILER. TO PREVENT ANY UNEXPECTED VENTING OF HYDROGEN GAS, THE TRAILER EXITED 1-75S AT EXIT 56 AND DRIVEN TO AN ABANDONED GAS STATION WHERE THE DRIVERS "BLEW DOWN" THE PRESSURE TO 75 PSIG. THE TRAILER CONTINUED TO MCINTOSH, AL WHERE THE PRESSURE HAD CLIMBED TO 120 PSIG. THE TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE AFTER THE VACUUM (PART OF THE INSULATING SYSTEM) WAS UNACCEPTABLY HIGH.

DRIVER TRAVIS RELIFORD MADE A PICK-UP AT LOWES ON 220 SOUTH. HE PLACED THE PACKAGE ON THE SHELF AND DROVE DOWN THE HIGHWAY TO HIS NEXT STOP. THE SMELL OF KEROSENE CAUSED THE DRIVER TO STOP AT HARDEES ON 220 TO INVESTIGATE. HE NOTICED THAT A PACKAGE THAT WAS PICKED UP FROM LOWES HAD A PICTURE OF A KEROSENE HEATER ON IT AND IT APPEARED TO HAVE A LIQUID LEAKING FROM IT. THE DRIVER CALLED THE DANVILLE CENTER AND WAS TOLD BY CENTER MANAGER BOB CALLIHAN TO SECURE THE VEHICLE AND WAIT FOR A FIRST RESPONDER. FIRST RESPONDER MAC MCGEE DROVE A REPLACEMENT VEHICLE TO THE DRIVER AND PACKAGES WERE DOWNLOADED TO THE REPLACEMENT VEHICLE. DECISION TREE WAS FOLLOWED AND PROCEDURE FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS WAS FOLLOWED. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THEY PICKED UP PACKAGE AND CONTENTS ON 6-11-97. SHIPPER WAS INFORMED OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS LABELING ON THIS PACKAGE WAS INCORRECT--THAT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGES MUST HAVE PROPER LABELING.

ON FRIDAY MORNING, JUNE 27, 1997, AT 4:00 AM, HOLNAM EMPLOYEES WERE PREPARING TO UNLOAD A RAIL CAR OF WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID WHEN THE MATERIAL WAS SPILLED INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AT THE UNLOADING AREA OF THE FACILITY. A FAULTY VALVE ON THE RAIL CAR CAUSED THE RELEASE. THE VALVE WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION EVEN THOUGH IT INDICATED IT WAS CLOSED. AN EMERGENCY VALVE THAT HAD BEEN DESIGNED BY THE FACILITY WAS PLACED ON THE RAIL CAR WHICH PREVENTED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS (17,000 GALLONS) FROM BEING RELEASED. APPROXIMATELY 3,306 GALLONS OF WASTE WAS SPILLED. THE WASTE WAS PUMPED FROM OUR CONTAINMENT PIT TO AN EMPTY TRAILER. IN OUR EFFORTS TO ATTACH THE EMERGENCY VALVE, ABOUT ONE GALLON OF WASTE WAS SPLASHED OUTSIDE OF OUR CONTAINMENT AREA. THE CONTAMINATED AREA COVERED ABOUT ONE SQUARE FOOT. THIS MATERIAL WAS IMMEDIATELY SHOVELED-UP AND PLACED INTO A DRUM THAT WILL BE DISPOSED OF OFF-SITE. EMERGENCY COORDINATORS IMPLEMENTED TO CONTINGENCY PLAN IMMEDIATELY, ASSESSING THE SITUATION AND MAKING NOTIFICATIONS TO THE PROPER AGENCIES. NO ONE WAS INJURED AND PROTECTION OF HUMAN HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT WERE THE TOP PRIORITIES TO THE PLANT TEAM AS THEY HANDLED THE INCIDENT. DETAILS OF THE FUEL ANALYSIS AND THE MANIFEST OF THE LOAD IN QUESTION ARE ATTACHED. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, CONCERNS OR COMMENTS, PLEASE CALL.

column168: AFTER COMPLETING THE DELIVERY OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE AT THE ORIGIN ADDRESS, OUR DELIVERY TRUCK PROCEEDED TO EXIT THE AREA.  THE EXIT ROUTE INCLUDED SEVERAL SPEED BUMPS.  AS OUR DRIVER APPROACHED THE "STOP" SIGN, HE NOTICED THE DELIVERY HOSE WAS BEING DRAGGED BEHIND THE TRUCK.  APPARENTLY, THE DELIVERY HOSE HAD BOUNCED OUT OF THE HOSE CAGE ON THE REAR OF THE TRUCK.  THE WEIGHT OF THE HOSE DRAGGING BEHIND THE TRUCK CAUSED THE BREAKGAGE OF THE NIPPLE AND "OFF VALVE" ON THE REAR OF THE TANKER, THUS DISCHARGING APPROXIMATELY 1500 GALLONS OF 12 1/2 % SODIUM HYPHOCHLORITE FROM OUR TANKER TO THE READWAY.  THE HOLE RESULTING FROM THE DAMAGED "OFF VALVE" WAS PLUGGED BY THE HAZMAT OR RESPONDING FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE TRUCK WAS RELOCATED TO A NEARBY STEEP EMBANKMENT UNTIL A NEW FITTING COULD BE INSTALLED.D  NO INDIVIDUAL WAS INJURED DUE TO THIS SPILLAGE.  5000 GALLONS OF WATER WERE REMOVED FROM A NEARBY DRAINAGE AREA. THE 500 GALLONS OF WATER WERE TREATED WITH THE CHLORINE NEUTRALIZER, SODIUM THIOSULPHATE AND DISPOSED OF BY INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICE, INC.  TO AVOID A SIMILAR INCIDENT IN THE FUTURE, OUR HOSES WILL BE SECURED AND CLAMPED BEFORE INITIATION OF MOVEMENT BY THE DELIVERY VEHICLE.

column168: ON FRIDAY, JUNE 6, 1997, AT APPROXIMATELY 2:35 P.M., DIXON BROS., INC., DRIVER, STEVE LOZINSKI WAS TO DELIVER 10,700 GALLONS OF JET A TO LYNCH FLYING SERVICE, BILLINGS, MT FOR BIG SKY AIRLINES. UPON ARRIVING AT THE UNLOADING SITE, THE F.B.O CUSTOMER REP DAN DOMEK PERFORMED THE API TEST, WHITE BUCKET TEST, SET THE VALVES TO TANK #3 AND WENT TO TAKE THE TANK INVENTORY.   WHEN HE WAS TAKING THE TANK INVENTORY, THE TAPE STUCK IN THE MACHINE AND DID NOT PRINT. ASSUMING EVERYTHING WAS OK HE THEN INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER THAT IT WAS OK  TO UNLOAD.  THE DRIVER THEN STARTED TO MAKE HIS DELIVERY.  DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, TANK #3 FILLED TO CAPACITY AND STARTED TO RUN OVER.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE PUMP AND CLOSED THE VALVE BETWEEN THE TRANSPORT AND THE PUMP.  HE THEN WALKED OVER TO A BUILDING APPROXIMATELY 150-200 YARDS FROM THE UNLOADING AREA AND USED A TELEPHONE TO CALL LYNCH FLYING SERVICE TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  LYNCH FLYING SERVICE IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED TO THE UNLOADING AREA.  THEY MADE CONTACT WITH CRAIG STAGNER, MT STATE LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY CONTROL, OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL, AND SHANE GETTERLING, OPERATIONS MANAGER OF CRASH CONTROL OF THE AIRPORT FACILITY.  THE DRIVER THEN FINISHED DELIVERING THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT IN TANK #1, UNHOOKED FROM THE DELIVERY PIPING AND ANSWERED ANY QUESTIONS THAT THE F.B.O OR OTHER OFFICIALS NEEDED TO HAVE ANSWERED.  DRIVER THEN RETURNED DIRECTLY TO THE DIXON BROS., INC. TERMINAL TO REPORT THE INCIDENT AND FILED AN INCIDENT REPORT (SEE ATTACHMENT #1) WITH DIXON BROS., INC. TERMINAL MANAGER STEVE BERGGUIST. STEVE BERGGUIST IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED EXXON CO., U.S.A. PERSONNEL KRIS GAGNON AND JERRY HARTNETT.

column168: WCAHM5A9701596 DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY DENVER NOTIFICATIONS DESK, WHO REPORTED BEING CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY FORCES.  SECURITY WAS REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER BEING IF LOADED FROM AN INBOUND (WESTBOUND) TRAIN. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF AND LOCATED THE CONTAINER, SPUL 21013 AND TPHU 636028, IN THE BOTTOM WELL OF A DOUBLE STACK CAR DROTT TRACK 802. THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER WERE POSITIONED WITH THE END DOORS FACING EACH OTHER IN THE CENTER OF THE CAR.  A SMALL POOL MEASURING ROUGHLY ONE FOOT IN RADIUS, WAS ON THE PAVEMENT DIRECTLY BELOW THE CENTER OF THE CAR, ON THE WEST SIDE OF THE TRACKAGE.  THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF DRIED RESIDUE ON THE INSIDE WEST SIDE RAIL OF THE CAR, INDICATING THE CONTENTS HAD BEEN LEAKING FOR A PERIOD OF TIME PRIOR TO ARRIVING AT THE ICTF.  AT THIS POINT, THE TERMINAL MANAGER ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION AND ADVISED SEVERAL EMPLOYEES HAD COMPLAINED OF EXPOSURE TO THE PRODUCT AND THEY HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED BY COMPANY VEHICLE TO THE LOCAL MEDICAL CLINIC.  MANAGER COOPER WAS REQUESTED TO TALK WITH THE ON DUTY PHYSICIAN AT THE CLINIC IN RELATION TO THE EXPOSURE.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE CLINIC WITH THE TERMINAL MANAGER AFTER THE AREA ONE CAR LENGTH FROM THE SPILL WAS SECURED AND MANNED BY SECURITY.  WHILE ENROUTE TO THE CLINIC, ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICES ARRANGED TO HAVE THE CONTAINERS REMOVED FROM THE RAIL CAR, DIAPERED, PLACED ONTO CHASSIS, AND MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE THEY COULD BE INSPECTED. ONCE AT THE CLINIC, IT WAS NOTED THAT A TOTAL OF EIGHT EMPLOYEES HAD BEEN TREATED.  A DISCUSSION WITH THE PHYSICIAN DEVELOPED ALL HAD BEEN GIVEN A PULMONARY TEST AND BLOOD SAMPLES HAD BEEN OBTAINED FOR TOXICITY TESTING.  IN DISCUSSIONS WITH SEVERAL OF THE EMPLOYEES, DEVELOPED THE CRANE OPERATOR NOTED THE CONTAINER LEAKING WHILE IT WAS BEING REMOVED FROM THE WELL OF THE CAR AND BEING PLACED ONTO A CHASSIS. RATHER THAN LEAVE THE CONTAINER ON THE CHASIS, HE REMOVED IT AND PLACED IT BACK INTO THE WELL OF THE RAILCAR.  ONCE ALL OF THE EMPLOYEES COMPLETED THEIR EXAMINATIONS, THEY WERE DRIVEN BACK TO THE FACILITY TO FINISH THEIR INJURY PAPERWORK.  AT THIS POINT, THERE WAS NO LOST EMPLOYEE TIME FROM THIS INCIDENT.  UPON RETURNING TO THE ICTF, MANAGER COOPER MET WITH DON TAGUE, LOCAL MANAGER FOR BAYER CORPORATION OUT OF THEIR CARSON FACILITY. THE DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT WERE  DISCUSSED AND THE PROTOCOL FOR ADDRESSING THE LEAKING LOAD DEVELOPED.  ONCE THE ETS CREW RETURNED FROM DECONING THE RAILCAR AND PAVEMENT AREA, THE CONTAINERS WERE REINSPECTED.  THE TPHU 63028 CONTAINER WAS NOT LEAKING AND ONLY HAD SMALL AMOUNT OF RESIDUE ON THE UNDER CARRIAGE. THE LEAKING CONTAINER, SPLU 21013, WAS THEN OPENED AFTER REMOVING SEAL BAYER 85035.  THE BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS IN CONFORMANCE WITH AAR BOE 6C, UTILIZING 4 EACH 2X6 CROSS MEMBERS AND 4 EACH 2X6 UPRIGHTS, WITH 2 SHEETS OF PLYWOOD PLACED ON END BETWEEN THE LUMBER AND THE LADING.  ONCE THE BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS REMOVED, OBSER

CENEX DRIVER, LYNN PRESTWICH, ARRIVED AT CENEX SPLY & MKTG (A.K.A. CSM) FARM ACCOUNT CALLED JONES FARMS. THE BULK DRIVER FROM CSM, MIKE, MET THE CENEX DRIVER AT THE FARM TO ASSIST IN THE DELIVERY. HIGH SULFUR DIESEL WAS BEING DELIVERED INTO THE FARMERS STORAGE VESSEL AT THE FARM, A 2-AXLE SINGLE COMPARTMENT TRAILER. THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE CUSTOMER'S TANK WAS LEAKING FROM THE BELLY OF THE TRAILER AND IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT INTO THE TANK AND BEGAN TO DIKE THE AREA TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. HE THEN CALLED CENEX DISPATCH IN PASCO, WA AND REPORTED THE SPILL TO DISPATCHER, DAVE BENDER. DAVE CALLED JIM WROGE WHO, IN TURN, NOTIFIED WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANTS FOR FURTHER ASSISTANCE IN RESPONDING TO THE INCIDENT. JOHN WILLIAMS, THE GENERAL MANAGER OF CSM IN QUINCY WENT OUT TO THE FARM TO INVESTIGATE THE SPILL. THE CONTAMINATED SOILS WERE REMOVED AND PLACED ON PLASTIC AND THE STATE WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THE SPILL. WCEC VISITED THE SITE AND TOOK A SAMPLE OF THE CONTAMINATED SOILS FOR TESTING AND IS MANAGING THE DISPOSAL OF THE CONTAMINATED SOILS. THE SPILL IS CLEANED UP AND ALL PRODUCT IN THE CUSTOMER'S LEAKING TANK WAS PUMPED OUT AND DIVERTED INTO ANOTHER STORAGE TANK.

ON JULY 26 1997 AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 AM I RECEIVE A TELEPHONE CALL FROM PENNY MOORE A TELEVISION REPORTER WHO ASKED FOR MY EXPLANATION OF WHAT WAS GOING ON WITH OUR BULK CO2 TANK TRUCK THAT WAS BURNING ON THE HIGHWAY.  I ASKED HER FOR THE EXACT LOCATION OF THIS INCIDENT, AND PROMPTLY CALLED THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION OF OHIO HAZMAT DIVISION TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  I SPOKE TO DAN FISHER AND GAVE HIM MY CONTACT NUMBER, AND INFORMED HIM OF THE CONTENTS AND CAPACITY  OF THE TANK.  I THEN NOTIFIED OUR DISPATCH DEPARTMENT AS TO WHAT HAD TAKEN PLACE.  AND DIRECTED OUT OTHER DRIVER FOR THE COLUMBUS AREA TO GO DIRECTLY TO THE ACCIDENT SCENE AND OFFER ASSISTANCE. THE NUCO2 BULK TRUCK WAS ATTEMPTING TO MERGE ONTO I-71 IN DOWNTOWN COLUMBUS FROM I-670.  WHILE MAKING A LANE CHANGE THE TRAFFIC IN THE LANE HE WAS GOING INTO STOPPED SUDDENLY.  THE DRIVER APPLIED HIS BRAKES CAUSING HIS TRUCK TO SKID SIDEWAYS, RESULTING IN OUR TRUCK STRIKING THE REAR END OF THE SEMI-TRAILER THAT WAS STOPPED IN THE LANE IN FRONT OF OUR TRUCK.  AT THE MOMENT OF IMPACT,  THE STEERING COLUMN SEPARATED.  THEN THE TRUCK PROCEEDED OUT OF CONTROL AND CAME TO REST AGAINST A CONCRETE GUARD RAIL.  THE DRIVER RELEASED HIS SEATBELT AND JUMPED OUT OF THE TRUCK. THEN THE TRUCK CAUGHT FIRE. I RECEIVED A CALL A SHORT LATER FROM OUR OTHER DRIVER IN THE COLUMBUS AREA, INFORMING ME FROM THE ACCIDENT SCENE THAT THE FIRE WAS OUT, THE LIQUID CO2 FLOW HAD BEEN CONTAINED, AND THAT THE TRUCK WAS BEING TOWED.  I DISCOVERED LATER DURING AN INTERVIEW WITH DRIVER OF THE TRUCK INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT, THAT HE HAD BEEN DRIVING HIS TRUCK WITH CO2 SUPPLY VALVE TO THE HOSE REEL IN THE OPEN POSITION.  WHEN THE FIRE FROM THE TRUCK REACHED THE HOSE REEL, IT MELTED THE FILL GUN, AND ALLOWED LIQUID CO2 TO FLOW UNCONTROLLED FROM THE HOSE.  I HAVE SENT A MEMO OUT TO ALL PERSONNEL IN THE OPERATIONS DIVISION OF THE COMPANY TO MAKE CERTAIN THAT THEY: *WATCH FOR THEIR FOLLOWING DISTANCE  * ALWAYS SHUT OFF THE HOSE REEL SUPPLY VALVE AND BLOW DOWN THE HOSE REEL BEFORE MOVING THEIR TRUCK FROM ON ACCOUNT TO ANOTHER.  THIS WILL PREVENT A CO2 RELEASE LIKE THE ONE THAT OCCURRED.  IT WILL ALSO PROLONG THE LIFE OF THE HOSE AND THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVES ON THE FILL LINE. *ALWAYS WEAR THEIR SEATBELTS.  IT THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK IN THE ACCIDNET HADN'T BEEN WEARING HIS SEATBELT,  HE WOULD HAVE BEEN THROWN THROUGH THE WINDSHIELD.  IN THIS INSTANCE, HE WALKED AWAY FROM THE ACCIDNET. OUR AREA SUPERVISORS WILL BE CHECKING EVERY DEPOT TO ENSURE THAT THESE INSTRUCTIONS ARE BEING FOLLOWED.

AT APPROXIMATELY 12:45 PM, 6-25-1997, JOHN BYRD, THE APRIA HEALTH CARE EMPLOYEE INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT, WAS DRIVING APRIA HEALTHCARE TRUCK  #29023, A 1995 FORD VAN, WHEN HE WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT AT THE INTERSECTION OF 36TH AND "MN" AVE. , KALAMAZOO COUNTY, MI.  THE APRIA TRUCK WAS STRUCK ON THE RIGHT SIDE AND CAME TO REST IN A CORN FIELD. OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID APPROXIMATELY 150 GALLONS WAS RELEASED INTO THE OPEN FIELD.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT NO CLEANUP WAS REQUIRED. KALAMAZOO COUNTY SHERIFFS OFFICE WAS CONTACTED AND THEY COMPLETED THEIR REPORTS. THE RELEASE WAS APPARENTLY CAUSED BY INTERNAL MALFUNCTION, WHICH HAS NOT BEEN IDENTIFIED.  THE TANK MANUFACTURE HAS BEEN CONTACTED AND THE TANK WILL BE EXAMINED.

PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED BETWEEN TRACKS 47 & 48, MEASURING APPROXIMATELY 5 X 60 FEET, WITH NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS AFFECTED. MGR LERCH ADVISED THE SHIPPER AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER THE LOAD INTO TANK CAR TGOX 1310.  WITH THE USE OF ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTION INC, CONTRACTED BY SHIPPER, THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF CTS MGR LERCH.  UPON COMPLETION OF TRANSFER, TANK CAR UTLX 801421 WAS STENCILED "LEAKY TANK DON NOT LOAD" AND A "X" WAS SPRAY PAINTED AT THE POINT OF RELEASE.  CAR WAS THEN BAD  ORDERED TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS. NOTIFICATIONS:1200 HOURS,6-15-97, US AGRIUM, DOUG GRAUNKE, OPERATIONS MGR,; 1345 HOURS, NE. DEPARTMENT ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, JIM BOROVICH, #061597-JB1345.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW, WAS NOTIFIED BY RISK MANAGER CENTER, DENVER, THAT TANK CAR GATX 9858, MTBE WAS LEAKING ON SPRY INTERCHANGE TRACKS, OGDEN, UT.  DURING TRAVEL TO OGDEN, WAS NOTIFIED THAT OGDEN FIRE DEPARTMENT , HAZ MAT TEAM WAS AT THE SCENE.  CONTACTED CAPTAIN ORTON, WHO ADVISED THAT TANK CAR, WITH ONE NUT LOOSE.  AFTER SECURING HUNT, THE LEAK HAD SLOWED DOWN. INSTRUCTED CAPTION ORTON TO RELIEVE PRESSURE. ORTON ADVISED THAT THEY REDUCED THE PRESSURE, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. FURTHER HE ADVISED THAT ABOUT 200 -300 GALLONS HAD SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. AT 2300 HOURS, ARRIVED ON SCENE, INSPECTION REVEALED THAT WHERE THE 3 INCHES UNLOADING CONNECTION VALVE IS BOLTED TO THE EDUCTION NOZZLE, THE RUBBER GASKET BETWEEN VALVE AND NOZZLE HAD FAILED.  REMOVED OLD GASKET, REPLACED WITH CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF ABOVE EXCEPTIONS.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT SEAL: KELLER SEALS 15339039, WAS REMOVED BY OGDEN FIRE DEPARTMENT, TO VIEW AREA AND REDUCE LEAK. MTBE AT SPILL AREA HAD VAPORIZED.

column62: Overfilled; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, VERN LIBBY, WAS ADVISED BY PHIL THOMPSON, RTS SUPERVISOR AT SEATTLE, THAT TRAILER XTRZ 632968, PLACARDED FLAMMABLE, 3, UN1987 HAD JUST ARRIVED ON TRAIN ZPDSE 25, SPOTTED TO RAMP TRACK 3, AN HAD BEEN NOTED TO BE LEAKING. INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED TRAILER TO BE LOADED WITH 13 - 300 GALLON BULK DRUMS CONTAINING ALCOHOLS NOS, TETROLITE SCALE INHIBITOR SCW839G.  ALL 13 BULK DRUMS APPEARING TO BE OVERFILLED.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THERE HAD BEEN ATTEMPT TO BLOCK AND BRACE THE LOAD.  HOWEVER, AT THE TIME OF INTERIOR INSPECTION, ALL BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS LYING LOOSE AND NOT PROTECTING.  LIBBY CONTACTED JOE DEBNAM, CHEMTREC, WHO PUT HIM IN CONTACT WITH JOHN HARDEN, PETROLITE CHEMICAL, AND ALSO ASSIGNED CHEMTREC CASE #56367 TO THIS INCIDENT.  JOHN HARDEN CONTRACTED DIRECTLY WITH FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL TO CLEAN STACKCAR TTOX 145285, TRAILER XTRZ 632969, AND THE NINE BULK DRUMS, WHICH WERE LEAKING AND SECURE THEM FOR FURTHER SHIPMENT OT ALASKA..

ON 6-25-97 LEAD SORTER, BARRY COCHRAN REPORTED A SHIPMENT LEAKING AND EMITTING AN ODOR IN THE MAIN SORT FACILITY OF ABX AIR, INC. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, ALAN HENDERSON RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS ISOLATED. TECHNICIAN HENDERSON DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX. INSIDE THERE WERE TWO METAL, FRICTION TYPE RECEPTACLES. EACH HAVING ONE QUART CAPACITY. THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THESE CLOSURES. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZMAT SORT IN THE SECURITY CAGE, UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

JUNE 22,1997- DAY 1 3:00 P.M. RECEIVED INITIAL CALL FROM OTTO BRINK, R&R TRUCKING. RECEIVED INFO ON SPILL/ACCIDENT IN COLORADO. INFORMED HIM THAT HMRI COULD RESPOND AND HANDLE SITUATION. HE IS WAITING ON CALL FROM ARMY EOD AND COLORADO HAZMAT BEFORE TEAM SENT. 4:00 P.M. CONTACTED R & R FOR UPDATE, RECEIVED PHONE NUMBERS FOR ON-SITE PERSONNEL AND EOD OFFICE IN COLORADO. 4:45 P.M. CONTACTED MASTER SERGEANT MAXIE OF EOD OPERATIONS IN FT. CARSON. RECEIVED INFO ON SPILL. INFORMED HIM OF MY STATUS AS FORMER EOD OFFICER IN US ARMY. DISCUSSED OPTIONS IN SPILL CLEANUP. 5:00 P.M. CONTACTED ON-SITE COLORADO HAZMAT AND EOD PERSONNEL. SPOKE TO MIKE COOK OF COLORADO HAZMAT, AND STAFF SERGEANT DANJOU FROM THE 764TH EOD. RECEIVED INFO ON SPILL/ACCIDENT. SPOKE TO FRANK BRISWELL OF R&R TRUCKING. RECEIVED VERBAL CONFIRMATION TO RESPOND TO INCIDENT SITE. CONTACTED OTTO BRINK TO VERIFY INSTRUCTIONS AND FAXED AUTHORIZATION FOR SERVICES AGREEMENT TO HIM. CONTACTED TEAM AND DEPARTED FOR SITE. 6:30 P.M. DEPARTED OLATHE AIRPORT FOR BURLINGTON COLORADO AIRPORT. 8:15 P.M. ARRIVE BURLINGTON CO. AIRPORT. RECEIVED POLICE ESCORT TO SITE. 8:30 P.M. ARRIVE ON SITE. PROVIDE COLORADO HAZMAT WITH VERIFICATION OF INSURANCE AND TRAINING CERTIFICATES. MEET WITH THE FOLLOWING: COLORADO HAZMAT: JIM KRUG AND MIKE COOK. US ARMY EOD: SSG DANJOU AND SPEC. 4 LEONARD. RECEIVED INFO ON WHAT THEY REQUIRED AS TO RESPONSE AND INFO ON AMMUNITION INVOLVED. VIEWED ACCIDENT SITE, DID SITE SAFETY PLAN, REMOVED ALL LIVE FULL UP ROUNDS FROM HARD SURFACE ROAD WAY AND PLACED INTO SAFE AREA. DEVELOPED PLAN FOR CLEANUP PROCEDURES. SINCE I-70 IS SHUT DOWN WITH TRAFFIC REROUTED TO SECONDARY ROUTES AND DUR TO ONCOMING DARKNESS, IT WAS DECIDED TO SHUT THE SITE DOWN UNTIL NEXT MORNING. WILL BEGIN OPERATIONS AT 07:00 A.M. JUNE 23,1997. STATE POLICE WILL SECURE THE SITE UNTIL THEN. 10:45 DEPART SITE FOR HOTEL. 11:00 ARRIVE AT HOTEL. CONTACT RESPONSE TEAM AND INFORM THEM WHERE TO COME TO AND WHAT TIME TO BEGIN OPERATIONS.
